Case/When
---------

case(x,
   when(A, B, "plus" println),
   when(C, "minus" println),
   else("foo" println)
)

case(
   when(X == X, "plus" println),
   when(X == Y, "plus" println),
   else("something")
)

The difference is that case will return the result of the first matching when. You can use when outside of case too.

when should return "nomatch" instead of "nil" when failing...
